					<p>We observed and talked with novice speakers and interviewed two professional oral communicator lecturers - <a href='https://www.linkedin.com/pub/matt-vassar/28/196/798'>Matt Vassar</a> and <a href='http://vpuewh-public.stanford.edu/viewprofile.jsp?sunetid=sohui&usetype=P&userid=PWR'>Sohui Lee</a>. We learned one of the biggest problems students have is maintaining steady eye gaze and vocal variation. Video recording, the most common debugging method, is typically ineffective due to its awkwardness. </p>

					<blockquote>Time and sound [are] so warped when you’re presenting. Ten minutes can feel like forever! <footer>- Dr. Sohui Lee</footer></blockquote>

					<p>Conversations with and observations of novice speakers surfaced further issues. When told to pay attention to a particular presentation aspect, students either briefly correct the feature or are thrown off their presentation entirely. Immediate feedback is useful, but only in small doses. From this exploration, narrowed our problem space: non-professional oral presenters need a way to receive small amounts of immediate and intimate feedback and then later analyze details of their performances. 
